\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Positive correlations among fecundity components boost estimates of local
 adaptation in
\emph on
 Arabidopsis thaliana
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Thomas James Ellis, Froukje Postma, Chris Oakley, Jon Ã…gren
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Local adaptation can be expressed through several components of fitness,
 some of which may be linked by trade-offs.
 Assessments of the strength of local adaptation and its genetic basis should
 thus include as many components of fitness as possible.
 We quantified local adaptation and examined its genetic basis by mapping
 quantitative trait loci (QTL) for fitness and its components in a population
 of recombinant inbred lines (RILs) derived from a cross between two locally
 adapted populations of Arabidopsis thaliana planted at the sites of the
 two source populations in two years.
 We specifically examined whether number of seeds per fruit is negatively
 correlated with fruit production or seed size, and thus whether the inclusion
 of this fitness component would reduce estimates of local adaptation.
 The local genotype outperformed the non-local genotype in terms of both
 number of fruits and number of seeds per fruit.
 In the RIL population, the two fecundity components were positively correlated,
 and fecundity was positively correlated with survival.
 We found only limited evidence of a trade-off with seed size.
 With a few exceptions, QTL for number of fruits and number of seeds per
 fruit mapped to the same genomic regions, with allelic effects in the same
 direction.
 The results suggest that estimates of the strength of local adaptation
 increase if both fecundity components are considered, and that variation
 in overall vigour rather than trade-offs underlie differences observed
 in individual components of fecundity and fitness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding the processes governing life-history evolution and local adaptatio
n is of fundamental interest in evolutionary biology, but is also of considerabl
e interest in applied fields such as agriculture, forestry, and conservation
 biology 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "williams1966,kawecki2004conceptual"

\end_inset

.
 Selection can act on multiple components of fitness, such as survival probabili
ty, offspring number and offspring size 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fisher1930"

\end_inset

.
 However, because resources are finite, increased investment in one component
 must come at the expense of all others, leading to trade-offs among life-histor
y traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "smith1958effects,stearns1992"

\end_inset

.
 Adaptation to a novel environment may thus be associated with a shift in
 allocation strategy to optimise the balance between fitness components
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lack1954natural,williams1966natural,de1992acquisition"

\end_inset

.
 At the same time, adaptation may also be associated with an increased ability
 to acquire resources in the new environment, which allows for increased
 investment in multiple component of fitness simultaneously 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vannoordwijk1986"

\end_inset

.
 These two processes have distinct implications for local adaptation, because
 trade-offs will place a constraint on adaptive evolution, while increased
 resource acquisition will facilitate it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Variation in allocation strategy and resource acquisition have distinct
 effects on genetic and phenotypic variation when we compare locally-adapted
 and non-locally-adapted genotypes.
 If there are trade-offs among fitness components, these should be manifested
 as negative genetic correlations among constituent traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stearns1992"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we would expect underlying quantitative trait loci (QTL) to show
 antagonistic pleiotropic effects, whereby an allele is associated with
 a positive effect on one trait, and a negative effect on another 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hazel1943genetic,falconer&mackay1996,mojica2012spatially"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if variation in resource acquisition is large, we expect
 positive genetic correlations among traits and positive pleiotropic QTL
 effects, with alleles being associated with increase or decrease in both
 phenotypes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vannoordwijk1986,houle1991genetic"

\end_inset

.
 In reality both processes may be acting, and the relative strength of trade-off
s and variation in resource status will be reflected in a continuum of negative
 to positive correlations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To elucidate how these processes contribute to local adaptation, it is necessary
 to compare locally-adapted and non-locally adapted genotypes at their native
 sites in reciprocal transplant experiments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kawecki2004conceptual"

\end_inset

.
 There is abundant evidence of trade-offs among fitness components within
 natural populations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "references in"
key "stearns1992"

\end_inset

.
 However, since these comparisons consider genotypes that are presumably
 already locally adapted, they tell us little about the processes that brought
 about that adaptation.
 Reciprocal transplant experiments frequently show that local genotypes
 outperform immigrant genotypes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hereford2009quantitative,leimu2008meta"

\end_inset

, but it is not clear whether this entails correlated changes in fitness
 components.
 A limited number of studies have attempted to map and investigate pleiotropic
 effects of QTL for fitness components in transplant experiments, and have
 found evidence of antagonistic pleiotropy of allelic effects on flowering
 and survival 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "anderson2014strong"

\end_inset

 and on seed number per fruit and seed mass 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "verhoeven2004genetic"

\end_inset

.
 We currently know little about whether adaptation is driven by positive
 or negative pleiotropic effects, nor whether patterns at the phenotypic
 level are reflected in allelic effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For annual plants, we can expect trade-offs between three pairs of traits
 to be especially relevant for overall fitness.
 Firstly, we might expect a negative correlation between fecundity and survival.
 Plant survival is typically correlated with plant size, and growth depends
 on meristems, which can develop into either vegetative or reproductive
 tissue.
 Since these outcomes are mutually exclusive, a trade-off between reproduction
 and growth (and hence survival) is expected 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "geber1990cost"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, resources allocated to reproduction are not available for
 investment in defence against parasites and predators, or abiotic stressors
 such as cold 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bazzaz1987allocating"

\end_inset

, which may further reduce probability of survival.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, total seed production is a function of the number of fruits produced
 and the number of seeds per fruit, and there may be a trade-off between
 these components of fecundity.
 For practical reasons studies of local adaptation in plants typically focus
 on either fruit production or estimates of total seed production as a measure
 of fecundity (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "latta2009testing,hall2010local,fournier2011map,hancock2011adaptation,agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

), whereas seed production per fruit under field conditions has received
 relatively cursory attention (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "maddox1983experimental,verhoeven2004genetic,hall2006divergent,agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

).
 If these two components of fecundity are negatively correlated, variation
 in fruit production will overestimate variation in total fecundity, whereas
 the opposite is true if they are positively correlated.
 This implies that any relationship other than zero correlation will incorrectly
 estimate adaptive differentiation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A trade-off is also expected between investment into offspring size and
 number 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lack1954natural,smith1974optimal"

\end_inset

.
 This is expressed through a trade-off between seed size and number 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "harper1970,leishman2000evolutionary"

\end_inset

, meaning selection for larger offspring may thus constrain the evolution
 of increased fecundity.
 Negative genetic correlations between seed size and number have been documented
 across species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sera2004number"

\end_inset

 and within crop species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sadras2007evolutionary"

\end_inset

.
 However, variation in seed number is often orders of magnitude greater
 than variation in seed mass 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "harper1970"

\end_inset

.
 Seed mass is also strongly dependent on the resource status of the mother,
 and whereas seed number directly influences adult fitness, selection on
 seed mass acts only through indirect effects on offspring fitness 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "venable1992size"

\end_inset

.
 As such studies of natural plant populations have found that both the sign
 and magnitude of phenotypic and genetic correlations between seed size
 and number vary from negative to positive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "silvertown1989paradox,venable1992size"

\end_inset

.
 The extent to which seed mass constrains fecundity is likely to depend
 on the specific local conditions in which they evolve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, we investigate correlations among fitness components and
 map their genetic basis in 
\emph on
Arabidopsis thaliana
\emph default
 using recombinant inbred lines (RILs) derived from a cross between two
 locally adapted populations located close to the southern (Italy) and close
 to the northern (Sweden) margin of the native range in Europe.
 Reciprocal transplants have shown that the two source populations display
 strong adaptive differentiation expressed through higher survival and fruit
 production of the local genotype 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012,agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

, and QTL mapping identified a total of 15 QTL affecting an estimate of
 overall fitness (number of fruits per planted seedling; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

).
 However, this estimate of overall fitness does not consider possible variation
 in seed production per fruit, and it is therefore not clear how inclusion
 of this fitness component would affect estimates of selection and the genetic
 basis of fecundity and overall fitness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we investigate the contribution of individual components of fitness
 to local adaptation, and the correlation relationships between them.
 We first quantify seed output per fruit and mean seed size of the parental
 genotypes and of >300 RILs planted at the sites of the source populations
 in two years.
 We combine these data with previously published data on survival and fruit
 production to ask: (1) Does the local genotype produce more seeds per fruit
 compared to the non-local genotype, which would result in an even larger
 estimate of selection against the non-local genotype than previously reported
 based on fruit production only? (2) Are genetic correlations between fecundity
 and survival, between components of fecundity (number of fruits and number
 of seeds per fruit), and between offspring number and size negative or
 positive? (3) Do mapping results indicate pleiotropic effects of QTL for
 individual fitness components on other components of fitness, and are these
 effects positive or negative?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Materials and methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data collection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimated number of seeds per fruit and mean seed mass for recombinant
 inbred lines (RIL) and parental accessions in reciprocal transplant experiments
 at the native sites of the source populations over two years.
 These experiments have previously been described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

.
 In each site-year combination we sampled a single mature fruit from between
 1917 and 2359 RIL and between 79 and 189 parental plants, and counted and
 weighed all seeds per fruit on a Metler Toledo AT261 balance.
 We calculated mean seed mass as the mass of all seeds in a fruit, divided
 by the total number of seeds.
 We estimated mean values for each line in each site-year combination as
 the mean across all individuals of the same genotype.
 After excluding lines with fewer than three replicate individuals per line,
 we were able to estimate values for seed number per fruit and seed mass
 for between 340 and 389 RILs for each site-year combination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also compared RIL line means for seed number per fruit and seed mass
 with previously published data on (1) survival to reproduction, (2) number
 of fruits per reproductive plant (a measure of fecundity), and (3) number
 of fruits per planted seedling (a measure of overall fitness) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, we combined these datasets to estimate proxies for total fecundity
 and total fitness.
 We estimated seed number per reproductive plant as the product of fruit
 number per reproductive plant and seed number per fruit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "maddox1983experimental"

\end_inset

.
 Likewise, we estimated seed number per planted seedling as the product
 of fruit number per seedling by fruit number per plant.
 Since we did not have data on seed number per fruit for all individuals
 for which data on fruit number was available, we instead multiplied line-mean
 seed number by individual fruit number values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data handling and statistical analyses were performed in RStudio 1.0.153 using
 R 3.4.2 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "r_core_team,rstudio"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fitness differences between parental lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess the relative impact of fitness components on adaptive differentiation
 we quantified selection against the non-local genotype by calculating selection
 coefficients based on individual components of fitness, and on estimates
 of overall fitness.
 We calculated selection coefficients as 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1-w_{A}/w_{B}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the fitness of the local genotype and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{B}$
\end_inset

 that of the non-local genotype 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gillespie2010population"

\end_inset

.
 We calculated selection coefficients for overall fitness in terms of both
 fruit number per seedling and seed number per seedling, reflecting fitness
 estimates excluding and including information on seed number.
 We also estimated selection coefficients for two components of fecundity
 (fruit number per reproductive plant and seed number per fruit) and survival.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimated confidence intervals for selection coefficients by non-parametric
 bootstrapping.
 We resampled the data for each experiment with replacement 1000 times and
 calculated selection coefficients for each bootstrap sample.
 We estimated 95% confidence intervals for each coefficient as the 25th
 and 975th quantifies of these values.
 We estimated two-tailed 
\emph on
p-
\emph default
values for the null hypothesis that there is no adaptive differentiation
 as the twice the proportion of bootstrap values overlapping zero.
 It is more difficult to determine whether selection coefficients for the
 two measures of overall fitness, fruit number per reproductive plant and
 seed number per reproductive plant, differ from one another because these
 estimates are based on common data on fruit number, and as such are not
 independent.
 Rather than perform a formal test, we instead simply asked whether the
 coefficient for seed number per reproductive plant was beyond the 95% confidenc
e interval for the coefficient for fruit number per reproductive plant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Correlations between traits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess the strength of trade-offs among fitness components we calculated
 Spearman's rank correlation coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, between RIL means for each site-year combination.
 We examined relationships between three pairs of traits: (1) components
 of fecundity (fruit number per reproductive plant and seed number per fruit),
 (2) survival and fecundity (seed number per reproductive plant), and (3)
 fecundity and offspring size (seed number per reproductive plant and mean
 seed mass).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A small number of lines appeared to be outliers that showed showed low fecundity
 but unusually high seed mass (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter-plots"

\end_inset

).
 To exclude the possibility that these lines could unduly inflate correlation
 coefficients we repeated the analyses for fecundity and offspring investment
 excluding lines with mean seed mass greater than 35mg.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
QTL mapping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We mapped QTL for seed mass, seed number per fruit, and seed number per
 reproductive plant using the R/qtl package in R 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "broman2009guide,r_core_team"

\end_inset

.
 Mapping results for survival, fruit number per reproductive plant and fruit
 number per seedling have been previously described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

.
 We performed mapping for RIL mean data for each site-year combination separatel
y.
 We used Haleyâ€“Knott regression using genotype probabilities of the genetic
 markers and pseudomarkers in gaps >2 cM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "haley1992simple"

\end_inset

.
 We performed a two-QTL scan of the genome with 10,000 permutations of the
 phenotypic data to determine 5% LOD-significance thresholds for inclusion
 of QTL and epistatic interactions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "broman2009guide"

\end_inset

.
 Based on these thresholds, we used R/Tl's automated stepwise model selection
 procedure to identify significant additive QTL and epistatic interactions.
 We first applied a quantile normal transformation to phenotypes before
 model selection.
 Finally we used ANOVA on untransformed data to fit the multiple QTL model
 and calculate effect sizes with respect to the Swedish allele, as well
 as the proportion of the total phenotypic variance explained by each locus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We considered QTL identified for different sites, years or traits to colocalise
 to the same genomic region if the maximum-likelihood estimate of their
 positions were within 2cM of each other, or if the 95% Bayesian credible
 intervals for these estimates overlapped.
 We also excluded 'poorly-defined' QTL whose credible intervals for QTL
 position were less than 1/4 the length of the shortest chromosome (15.2cM;
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

) from further assessments of colocalisation, because such QTL provide little
 information about position 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_genetic_2013,oakley2014qtl,dittmar2014flowering,postma_early_2016"

\end_inset

.
 Based on these criteria, we identified a QTL as having pleiotropic effects
 on a pair of traits if QTL were detected in one or more years at a given
 site for both traits that colocalised to the same genomic region.
\end_layout

