\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our results demonstrate that positive correlations among these components
 contribute to the adaptive advantage of locally-adapted genotypes in 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana
\emph default
.
 When we include number of seeds per fruit in the estimate of fitness, the
 advantage of the local genotypes is greater than would be indicated based
 on survival and fruit production only in three of four site-year combinations.
 We found positive genetic correlations between components of fecundity
 in all site-year combinations, and between survival and fecundity in both
 years in Italy and in one year in Sweden.
 QTL-mapping revealed evidence of extensive pleiotropic effects on components
 of fecundity, and on fecundity and survival.
 In all but one case, QTL showed positive pleiototropic effects, with alleles
 being associated with an increase or decrease in both fitness components.
 These results indicate that variation in resource acquisition predominates
 over variation in resource-allocation strategy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vannoordwijk1986"

\end_inset

, and hence that selection for increased resource acquisition has played
 a major role in the process of local adaptation in these populations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Positive pleiotropy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found a marked tendency for QTL to have positive pleiotropic effects
 on multiple components of fitness.
 In all but one case, alleles at these loci were associated with changes
 in the same direction for both components of fecundity, and/or both survival
 and fecundity.
 This pattern is to be expected when QTL influence resource acquisition,
 which in turn allows for increased investment in multiple fitness components
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vannoordwijk1986,houle1991genetic"

\end_inset

.
 At the remaining locus at the end of chromosome 1 in Sweden in 2010, the
 local allele was associated with and increase in seed number per fruit
 but a decrease in fruit number per reproductive plant, reflecting a trade-off
 in allocation to these components of fecundity.
 Theory predicts that positive correlations among fitness components are
 expected at equilibrium of there are many more loci involved in resource
 acquisition than allocation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "houle1991genetic"

\end_inset

, as observed in 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana.
 
\emph default
These findings indicate that there is some variation in allocation strategy,
 but this is overwhelmed by variation in resource acquisition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observation of positive pleiotropy is in contrast to those found in
 the related species 
\emph on
Boechera stricta 
\emph default
using a similar experimental design.
 Here, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2014strong"

\end_inset

 found negative genetic correlations between fruit production and future
 reproduction, and antagonistic pleiotropic effects of QTL influencing these
 traits.
 One explanation for this discrepancy is that there could be higher dominance
 variance in 
\emph on
B.
 stricta 
\emph default
than 
\emph on
A thaliana
\emph default
 since negative pleiotropy is expected to be stronger if there is directional
 dominance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rose1982antagonistic,curtsinger1994antagonistic"

\end_inset

.
 However, since both species are mostly self-pollinating, this is unlikely.

\emph on
 A.
 thaliana
\emph default
 is a winter annual, and rapid autumn growth is associated with both high
 survival and increased fecundity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "akiyama2014conflicting"

\end_inset

.
 Efficient resource acquisition in autumn might therefore drive both survival
 and fecundity.
 Since 
\emph on
B.
 stricta 
\emph default
is perennial, there may be greater scope for variation in allocation strategy
 between current and future reproduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stearns1992"

\end_inset

.
 It is possible that broader life history strategy has important implications
 for the relative contribution of resource acquisition and allocation to
 local adaptation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Seed size and number
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our comparison of parental lines at each site showed that the relative importanc
e of seed number per fruit to other fitness components varied among site
 and year.
 In both years in Italy, the selective advantage of the local genotype through
 fruit number per plant was approximately twice as large as that through
 seed number per fruit (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
 Nevertheless, selection through seed number per fruit of 
\begin_inset Formula $s\geq0.33$
\end_inset

 represents strong selection, and is of similar magnitude to values compiled
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "endler1986"

\end_inset

 for fecundity traits in other systems.
 In Sweden in 2011, we detected selection through survival only, with no
 adaptive differentiation through either component of fecundity.
 By contrast, in 2010, selection through seed number per fruit was the only
 significant fitness component (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
 When fecundity was quantified as seed number per reproductive plant rather
 than fruit number only we were able to detect significant overall local
 advantage in overall fitness that would not have been detected had fecundity
 been estimated using fruit number per plant only.
 In addition, we were able to detect two additional QTL in Sweden with effects
 on seed number only (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:QTL-positions"

\end_inset

).
 These results illustrate that variation in seed number per fruit represents
 and important component of variation in overall fitness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found quite different patterns of covariation and genetic architecture
 for seed mass than for fitness components.
 On one hand, QTL for seed mass tended to have antagonistic pleiotropic
 effects on fecundity, and we found a weak trade-off between seed mass and
 fecundity in 2010 in Sweden (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter-plots"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:QTL-positions"

\end_inset

).
 Nevertheless, this correlation was weak, and we found no significant genetic
 correlation in Sweden in 2011 nor in Italy in either year (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter-plots"

\end_inset

), suggesting that any constraint imposed by seed mass on fecundity is small.
 Seed traits are distinct from the other traits considered in this study
 in that it is not components of fitness, but traits expected to influence
 fitness at germination and establishment, with cascading effects on later
 life-history stages 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moles2006seed,postma_early_2016"

\end_inset

.
 In this study we examined plants transplanted as seedlings and harvested
 as adults, and as such we were not able to detect possible early-stage
 fitness effects.
 It remains possible that an investigation focussing on offspring fitness
 would reveal a clearer pattern of the relationship between seed mass and
 fitness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, this study has demonstrated that local adaptation in A.
 thaliana is expressed through multiple components of fitness simultaneously,
 and that variation in seed number per fruit makes an important contribution
 to adaptive differentiation.
 Our results imply that variation in resource acquisition rather than resource
 allocation strategy is the main determinant in the differences in fecundity
 and fitness we observe.
 In ongoing work we are investigating adaptation to soil type and resource
 use to begin to elucidate the mechanisms which link resource acquisition
 to adaptive differentiation.
 
\end_layout

